  <exercise xml:id="ex_span_independence_transform">
    <title>Linear transformations, span, and independence</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>T\colon V\rightarrow W</m> is a linear transformation.   Let <m>S=\{\boldv_1,\boldv_2,\dots ,\boldv_r\}</m> be a subset of <m>V</m>, and let <m>S'</m> be the image of <m>S</m> under <m>T</m>: <ie />,
        <me>
          S'=T(S)=\{T(\boldv_1), T(\boldv_2),\dots, T(\boldv_r)\}
        </me>.
        Assume <m>\boldv_i\ne \boldv_j</m> and <m>T(\boldv_i)\ne T(\boldv_j)</m> for all <m>i\ne j</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Answer true or false: if true, provide a proof; if false, provide an explicit counterexample. Note: for a complete counterexample you need to specify <m>T\colon V\rightarrow W</m>, and <m>S</m>.
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
          If <m>S</m> is linearly independent, then <m>S'</m> is linearly independent.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>S'</m> is linearly independent, then <m>S</m> is linearly independent.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>S</m> is a spanning set for <m>V</m>, then <m>S'</m> is a spanning set for <m>\im T</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise xml:id="ex_transformation_reflection">
    <title>Reflection through a line</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Fix an angle <m>\alpha</m> with <m>0\leq \alpha \leq \pi </m>, let <m>\ell_\alpha</m> be the line through the origin that makes an angle of <m>\alpha</m> with the positive <m>x</m>-axis, and let <m>r_\alpha\colon\R^2\rightarrow \R^2</m> be the reflection operation as described in <xref ref="d_reflection"/>.
     Prove that <m>r_\alpha</m> is a linear transformation following the steps below.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              In a manner similar to <xref ref="th_transform_rotation"/>, describe <m>P'=r_\alpha(P)</m> in terms of the polar coordinates <m>(r,\theta)</m> of <m>P</m>. Additionally, it helps to write <m>\theta=\alpha+\phi</m>, where <m>\phi</m> is the angle the line segment from the origin to <m>P</m> makes with the line <m>\ell_\alpha</m>.
              Include a drawing to support your explanation.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Use your description in (a), along with some trigonometric identities, to show <m>r_\alpha=T_A</m> where
              <me>
                A=\begin{bmatrix}\cos 2\alpha \amp \sin 2\alpha\\ \sin 2\alpha \amp -\cos 2\alpha \end{bmatrix}
              </me>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise xml:id="ex_transformation_composition_rotations_reflections">
    <title>Compositions of rotations and reflections</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        In this exercise we will show that if we compose a rotation or reflection with another rotation or reflection, as defined in <xref ref="d_rotation"/> and <xref ref="d_reflection"/>, the result is yet another rotation or reflection.
        For each part, express the given composition either as a rotation <m>\rho_\theta</m> or reflection <m>r_\theta</m>, where <m>\theta</m> is expressed in terms of <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m>.
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
          <m>\rho_\alpha\circ\rho_\beta</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
          <m>r_\alpha\circ r_\beta</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
          <m>\rho_\alpha\circ r_\beta</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>r_\alpha\circ \rho_\beta</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
    <hint>
      <p>
        Use <xref ref="th_transform_rotation"/> and <xref ref="th_transform_reflection"/>, along with some trigonometric identities.
      </p>
    </hint>

  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The set <m>B=\{\boldv_1=(1,-1), \boldv_2=(1,1)\}</m> is a basis of <m>\R^2</m>. Suppose the linear transformation <m>T\colon \R^2\rightarrow \R^3</m> satisfies
        <me>
          T(\boldv_1)=(4,1,2), T(\boldv_2)=(1,0,2)
        </me>.
        Find a formula for <m>T(\boldx)</m>, where <m>\boldx=(x,y)</m> is a general element of <m>\R^2</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  
